# HTML Overview

HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the standard markup language for creating web pages and web applications. Let me create a comprehensive HTML example that demonstrates its key features.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>HTML Overview</title>
    <style>
        * {
            box-sizing: border-box;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
        }
        
        body {
            background-color: #f5f7fa;
            color: #333;
            line-height: 1.6;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        
        .container {
            max-width: 1200px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        
        header {
            background: linear-gradient(135deg, #6a11cb 0%, #2575fc 100%);
            color: white;
            padding: 40px 20px;
            border-radius: 10px;
            text-align: center;
            margin-bottom: 30px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }
        
        h1 {
            font-size: 2.8rem;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
        
        h2 {
            color: #2575fc;
            margin: 25px 0 15px;
            padding-bottom: 10px;
            border-bottom: 2px solid #eaeaea;
        }
        
        h3 {
            color: #6a11cb;
            margin: 20px 0 10px;
        }
        
        .intro {
            font-size: 1.2rem;
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: 0 auto;
        }
        
        .card {
            background: white;
            border-radius: 10px;
            padding: 25px;
            margin-bottom: 25px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
            transition: transform 0.3s ease;
        }
        
        .card:hover {
            transform: translateY(-5px);
        }
        
        .code-example {
            background-color: #2d2d2d;
            color: #f8f8f2;
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            margin: 15px 0;
            overflow-x: auto;
            font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
        }
        
        .tag {
            color: #f92672;
        }
        
        .attribute {
            color: #a6e22e;
        }
        
        .value {
            color: #fd971f;
        }
        
        .content {
            color: #f8f8f2;
        }
        
        .elements-grid {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(300px, 1fr));
            gap: 20px;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        
        .element-card {
            background: white;
            border-left: 4px solid #2575fc;
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
        }
        
        table {
            width: 100%;
            border-collapse: collapse;
            margin: 20px 0;
        }
        
        th, td {
            padding: 12px 15px;
            text-align: left;
            border-bottom: 1px solid #eaeaea;
        }
        
        th {
            background-color: #f1f5fd;
            color: #2575fc;
        }
        
        tr:hover {
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }
        
        form {
            background: white;
            padding: 25px;
            border-radius: 10px;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        
        .form-group {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 8px;
            font-weight: 600;
            color: #555;
        }
        
        input, select, textarea {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 12px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            border-radius: 5px;
            font-size: 1rem;
        }
        
        button {
            background: linear-gradient(135deg, #6a11cb 0%, #2575fc 100%);
            color: white;
            border: none;
            padding: 12px 25px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            font-size: 1rem;
            font-weight: 600;
            transition: all 0.3s ease;
        }
        
        button:hover {
            transform: translateY(-2px);
            box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        }
        
        footer {
            text-align: center;
            margin-top: 40px;
            padding: 20px;
            color: #777;
            border-top: 1px solid #eaeaea;
        }
        
        @media (max-width: 768px) {
            .elements-grid {
                grid-template-columns: 1fr;
            }
            
            h1 {
                font-size: 2.2rem;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>HTML Overview</h1>
            <p class="intro">HyperText Markup Language (HTML) is the standard markup language for documents designed to be displayed in a web browser.</p>
        </header>
        
        <div class="card">
            <h2>What is HTML?</h2>
            <p>HTML provides the structure of a webpage, consisting of a series of elements that tell the browser how to display content. HTML elements are represented by tags, which label pieces of content such as "heading", "paragraph", "table", and so on.</p>
            
            <div class="code-example">
                <pre><code>&lt;<span class="tag">!DOCTYPE html</span>&gt;
&lt;<span class="tag">html</span>&gt;
&lt;<span class="tag">head</span>&gt;
    &lt;<span class="tag">title</span>&gt;<span class="content">Page Title</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">title</span>&gt;
&lt;/<span class="tag">head</span>&gt;
&lt;<span class="tag">body</span>&gt;
    &lt;<span class="tag">h1</span>&gt;<span class="content">My First Heading</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">h1</span>&gt;
    &lt;<span class="tag">p</span>&gt;<span class="content">My first paragraph.</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">p</span>&gt;
&lt;/<span class="tag">body</span>&gt;
&lt;/<span class="tag">html</span>&gt;</code></pre>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card">
            <h2>Basic HTML Structure</h2>
            <p>Every HTML document follows a basic structure that includes the following elements:</p>
            
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Element</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</td>
                    <td>Defines the document type and HTML version</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>&lt;html&gt;</td>
                    <td>The root element of an HTML page</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>&lt;head&gt;</td>
                    <td>Contains meta information about the document</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>&lt;title&gt;</td>
                    <td>Specifies a title for the document</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>&lt;body&gt;</td>
                    <td>Contains the visible page content</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card">
            <h2>Common HTML Elements</h2>
            <p>HTML includes a wide variety of elements for structuring content. Here are some of the most commonly used ones:</p>
            
            <div class="elements-grid">
                <div class="element-card">
                    <h3>Headings</h3>
                    <p>&lt;h1&gt; to &lt;h6&gt; define HTML headings, with &lt;h1&gt; being the most important.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="element-card">
                    <h3>Paragraphs</h3>
                    <p>&lt;p&gt; defines a paragraph of text.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="element-card">
                    <h3>Links</h3>
                    <p>&lt;a&gt; defines a hyperlink to another webpage.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="element-card">
                    <h3>Images</h3>
                    <p>&lt;img&gt; embeds an image in the document.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="element-card">
                    <h3>Lists</h3>
                    <p>&lt;ul&gt;, &lt;ol&gt;, and &lt;li&gt; create unordered and ordered lists.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="element-card">
                    <h3>Tables</h3>
                    <p>&lt;table&gt;, &lt;tr&gt;, &lt;th&gt;, and &lt;td&gt; create tabular data.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card">
            <h2>HTML Forms</h2>
            <p>Forms are used to collect user input. Here's an example of a simple contact form:</p>
            
            <form>
                <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="name">Name:</label>
                    <input type="text" id="name" name="name" placeholder="Your name">
                </div>
                
                <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="email">Email:</label>
                    <input type="email" id="email" name="email" placeholder="Your email">
                </div>
                
                <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="subject">Subject:</label>
                    <select id="subject" name="subject">
                        <option value="general">General Inquiry</option>
                        <option value="support">Technical Support</option>
                        <option value="feedback">Feedback</option>
                    </select>
                </div>
                
                <div class="form-group">
                    <label for="message">Message:</label>
                    <textarea id="message" name="message" rows="5" placeholder="Your message"></textarea>
                </div>
                
                <button type="submit">Send Message</button>
            </form>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card">
            <h2>HTML5 Semantic Elements</h2>
            <p>HTML5 introduced semantic elements that clearly describe their meaning to both the browser and developer:</p>
            
            <div class="code-example">
                <pre><code>&lt;<span class="tag">header</span>&gt;<span class="content">Defines a header for a document or section</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">header</span>&gt;
&lt;<span class="tag">nav</span>&gt;<span class="content">Defines navigation links</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">nav</span>&gt;
&lt;<span class="tag">section</span>&gt;<span class="content">Defines a section in a document</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">section</span>&gt;
&lt;<span class="tag">article</span>&gt;<span class="content">Defines independent, self-contained content</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">article</span>&gt;
&lt;<span class="tag">aside</span>&gt;<span class="content">Defines content aside from the page content</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">aside</span>&gt;
&lt;<span class="tag">footer</span>&gt;<span class="content">Defines a footer for a document or section</span>&lt;/<span class="tag">footer</span>&gt;</code></pre>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <footer>
            <p>HTML is the foundation of web development. Combined with CSS for styling and JavaScript for interactivity, it enables the creation of modern, dynamic websites.</p>
            <p>© 2023 HTML Overview Example</p>
        </footer>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

This HTML document provides a comprehensive overview of HTML with:

1. A modern, responsive design
2. Examples of HTML structure and code
3. A table showing basic HTML elements
4. A working form example
5. Information about HTML5 semantic elements
6. Styled with CSS for better visual presentation

You can copy this code into an HTML file and open it in any browser to see the complete example.
